1. First, you'll need to create a new route in your Laravel application's `routes/api.php` file. Here's an example:
```php
Route::post('/reset-password', 'PasswordController@resetPassword');
```
This will create a new route for the `/reset-password` endpoint, which will use the `PasswordController` and the `resetPassword` method to handle password reset requests.

2. Next, you'll need to create a new controller in your Laravel application's `app/Http/Controllers` directory. Here's an example:
```php
<?php

namespace App\Http\Controllers;

use Illuminate\Http\Request;
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Auth;
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Hash;
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Validator;
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Mail;

class PasswordController extends Controller
{
    public function resetPassword(Request $request)
    {
        $validatedData = $request->validate([
            'token' => 'required|string',
            'new_password' => 'required|string|min:8',
        ]);

        $user = Auth::user()->where('token', $validatedData['token']);

        if ($user->exists()) {
            $user->update(['password' => Hash::make($validatedData['new_password'])]);
            $user->token = null;
            $user->save();

            Mail::to($user->email)->send(new PasswordResetSuccess($validatedData['new_password']));

            return response()->json([
                'message' => 'Password successfully reset.',
            ]);
        } else {
            return response()->json([
                'error' => 'Invalid token.',
            ]);
        }
    }
}
```
This controller defines a new method called `resetPassword` that will handle password reset requests. The method first validates the request data using Laravel's built-in validation system. It then retrieves the user associated with the provided token using Eloquent ORM.

If the user exists, the method updates the user's password using Laravel's built-in `Hash` facade and sets the user's token to `null` to indicate that the password has been reset. It then sends an email to the user using Laravel's built-in `Mail` facade.

If the user does not exist, the method returns an error response.

3. Finally, you'll need to create a new view or email template for the password reset success message. Here's an example:
```php
<?php

namespace App\Mail;

use Illuminate\Bus\Queueable;
use Illuminate\Mail\Message;
use Illuminate\Queue\SerializesModels;

class PasswordResetSuccess extends Message
{
    use Queueable, SerializesModels;

    /**
     * Create a new message instance.
     *
     * @return void
     */
    public function __construct($password)
    {
        $this->from('noreply@example.com', 'Your Name');

        $this->subject('Password Reset Success');

        $this->body('text', "Your password has been successfully reset to {$password}.");
    }
}
```
This view defines a new email template that will be sent to the user after their password has been successfully reset.

That's it! With these steps, you should now have a working password reset API endpoint in your Laravel application.

